items.preText: Thanks, Shashank. Imrul Kayes and Liton Das to open, Kyle Jarvis has the new ball. A wide slip in place. We're not far from the first ball. This is a good time to say hello to Hemant Brar. Steve Rhodes, the Bangladesh coach: "White ball cricket - to beat West Indies in both formats with the white ball, I was super impressed. Asia Cup, I think we could've played better, disappointed to lose the final but the guys came up with a superb effort. For the moment, a lot of the guys are going through a learning process." Ashik Mahmud: "Putting out talent like Shanto after only 3 matches is not justifiable. " Arun says: "Save for the exclusion of Cremer and the captaincy of Masakadza, this is the best Zimbabwe eleven possible. Finally sanity prevails in selection. The XIs for you Bangladesh: 1 Liton Das, 2 Imrul Kayes, 3 Fazle Mahmud, 4 Mushfiqur Rahim (wk), 5 Mohammad Mithun, 6 Mahmudullah, 7 Mehidy Hasan Miraz, 8 Mohammad Saifuddin, 9 Mashrafe Mortaza (capt), 10 Nazmul Islam, 11 Mustafizur Rahman Zimbabwe: 1 Hamilton Masakadza (capt), 2 Cephas Zhuwao, 3 Craig Ervine, 4 Brendan Taylor (wk), 5 Sean Williams, 6 Peter Moor, 7 Sikandar Raza, 8 Donald Tiripano, 9 Brandon Mavuta, 10 Kyle Jarvis, 11 Tendai Chatara 30-year old Fazle Mahmud debuts for Bangladesh. Selector Habibul Bashar thinks he is a complete package. He's a middle order batsman who made his debut in 2004, started off as a big-hitter but has mellowed down since into a build-an-innings batsman. Bangladesh win toss, opt to bat Not really a surprise considering how slow the surfaces in Mirpur have tended to be under lights. 1.50pm Bangladesh have a number of injury concerns. Shakib's recurring finger injury has ruled him out for another three months, while Tamim is yet to recover from the knuckle fracture he sustained after being struck by Suranga Lakmal in the opening Asia Cup match. Mashrafe and Mushfiqur have only recently recovered from injuries sustained in the same tournament, and neither is 100% fit. Even Mahmudullah was struggling with a little rib pain earlier this month. 1.30pm Warm welcome all. It's the start of Bangladesh's home winter. As they say, after the famine comes the feast. From the ball-by-ball team today, we've got myself, Shashank Kishore, and Hemant Brar to take you through the action as it unfolds in Mirpur. If you want to switch over to the India-West Indies ODI from time-to-time, not far away in Guwahati, you can join Deiva Muthu. We all know how strong Bangladesh are at home and this is an opportunity to firm up their plans for the 2019 World Cup. Zimbabwe, meanwhile, are coming off a tough, winless tour of South Africa - as you'd expect, if I may add - and here's an opportunity to showcase some improvements, perhaps even win. Over the years, they've had a number of famous contests. Can this series produce thrilling cricket?

items.text: slides one across at length, bunted into the off side.

items.shortText: Williams to Mohammad Saifuddin, no run
items.text: firmly driven but straight to cover.

items.shortText: Williams to Mohammad Saifuddin, 1 wide
items.text: sharp turn but this spins back in to beat the pad, good take by Taylor.

items.shortText: Williams to Mohammad Saifuddin, FOUR runs
items.text: rocks back and pulls this into the gap at deep midwicket. Poor ball, too short and he had all the time in the world to open up the leg side and power this away. Valiant effort by PJ Moor.

items.shortText: Williams to Mohammad Saifuddin, no run
items.text: eased back to the bowler, who fires a throw to the keeper. Saifuddin was outside the crease and had to scamper back through a dive

items.shortText: Williams to Mohammad Saifuddin, no run
items.text: dabs this gently from the crease.

items.shortText: Tiripano to Imrul Kayes, 1 wide
items.text: sways out of the line of this short delivery but it was sprayed far too wide outside off.

items.shortText: Tiripano to Imrul Kayes, 1 run
items.preText: The roar builds up again. Imrul on 99
items.text: there's his century! What a knock, what celebration! The cradle celebration. The dressing room is up on their feet to acknowledge a crucial knock. He got into of the bounce and turned this short of length delivery into the leg side for a quick single to bring up his landmark

items.shortText: Tiripano to Mohammad Saifuddin, 1 run
items.text: turns this wide of midwicket for another quick single.

items.shortText: Tiripano to Imrul Kayes, no run
items.preText: Danial: "Bangladesh needs this pair to carry on the good work till the 45th, then one of these guys need to stay till the end. Zimbabwe has shown great character so far! "
items.text: pulls and misses. This short delivery was angling away, he was through with the stroke way too early.

items.shortText: Tiripano to Imrul Kayes, no run
items.text: drills this full delivery straight to mid-off.

items.shortText: Tiripano to Imrul Kayes, no run
items.text: full and angling away, he bunts this into the off side for a quick single.

items.shortText: Tiripano to Imrul Kayes, FOUR runs
items.text: right in his half and he drills this into the gap at deep extra cover. Magnificent timing, even better placement. Raises the 200 for Bangladesh.

items.shortText: Chatara to Mohammad Saifuddin, no run
items.text: slices this lofted hit on the bounce to sweeper cover.

items.shortText: Chatara to Mohammad Saifuddin, 1 run
items.text: appeal for caught behind as he tries to deflect this full delivery wide of the keeper. The sound was that of bat touching the ground. Zimbabwe have reviewed anyway and it comes back a no-ball, so whatever happens after that goes out of the window. Let's move on. Chatara's front foot was on the line and that belongs to the umpire. Free-hit coming up

items.shortText: Chatara to Imrul Kayes, 1 no ball
Chatara to Imrul Kayes, 1 run
items.text: backs away, makes room and slaps this with all his might but on the bounce to the fielder at deep cover.

items.shortText: Chatara to Mohammad Saifuddin, no run
items.text: backs away to slap this over point but is beaten

items.shortText: Chatara to Mohammad Saifuddin, no run
items.text: keeps low as he stands tall to punch, pushed to cover.
